04428nam a22005655i 9780822395669DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20122013ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223956697 a10.1515/97808223956692doi  a(DE-B1597)553721  a(OCoLC)1202623175  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aHIS0410002bisacsh  aNO 88002rvk0(DE-625)rvk/127380:1 aJames, C. L. R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aToussaint Louverture :bThe Story of the Only Successful Slave Revolt in History; A Play in Three Acts‹br› /cC. L. R. James; Christian Høgsbjerg. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2012] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (236 p.) :b10 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe C. L. R. James Archives00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tForeword by Laurent Dubois -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tIntroduction -- tEditorial Note -- tAuthor's Note (1936) -- tThe Complete Playscript (1934) -- tAct II. Scene 1, from Toussaint Louverture (1936) -- tNotices -- tThe Programme (1936) -- tReviews -- t"The Intelligence of the Negro" -- t"A Century of Freedom" -- t"Slavery Today: A Shocking Exposure" -- t"I Want Negro Culture" -- t"'Civilising' the 'Blacks': Why Britain Needs to Maintain Her African Possessions" -- tLetter from George Padmore to Dr. Alain Locke -- t["The Maverick Club"] -- t"A Unique Personality" -- t"Paul Robeson" 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1934 C. L. R. James, the widely known Trinidadian intellectual, writer, and political activist, wrote the play Toussaint Louverture: The Story of the Only Successful Slave Revolt in History, which was presumed lost until the rediscovery of a draft copy in 2005. The play's production, performed in 1936 at London's Westminster Theatre with a cast including the American star Paul Robeson, marked the first time black professional actors starred on the British stage in a play written by a black playwright. This edition includes the program, photographs, and reviews from that production, a contextual introduction and editorial notes on the play by Christian Høgsbjerg, and selected essays and letters by James and others. In Toussaint Louverture, James demonstrates the full tragedy and heroism of Louverture by showing how the Haitian revolutionary leader is caught in a dramatic conflict arising from the contradiction between the barbaric realities of New World slavery and the modern ideals of the Enlightenment. In his portrayal of the Haitian Revolution, James aspired to vindicate black accomplishments in the face of racism and to support the struggle for self-government in his native Caribbean. Toussaint Louverture is an indispensable companion work to The Black Jacobins (1938), James's classic account of Haiti's revolutionary struggle for liberation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aRevolutionariesxDramaxHaiti. 0aSlaveryxDramaxHistoryxHaiti. 70(DE-588)4779423-90(DE-627)3721156080(DE-576)216313309aHaitianische Revolution2gnd 7aHISTORY / Caribbean & West Indies / General.2bisacsh1 aHøgsbjerg, Christian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822395669zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822395669423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822395669.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles